[normal]Q1 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair[bold]:[bold] 
[normal]First, may I apologise to you for the late-running of our Committee
[normal]?  
[normal]We are very grateful to you for joining us.  This is our first session on open data.  
[normal]C
[normal]ould
[normal] you
[normal] identify yourselves for the record, please
[normal]?
[normal]Professor Margetts[bold]:
[normal] 
[normal]I am Helen Margetts, Director of the Oxford Internet Institute.  
[normal]Dr Worthy:[bold] 
[normal]Benjamin Worthy
[normal], a lecturer in politics from Birkbeck College.  
[normal]Q2 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair[bold]:[bold] 
[normal]Thank you very much for being with us.  
[normal]May 
[normal]I suggest that
[normal],
[normal] if you feel we are not asking the right questions
[normal],
[normal] you give us the information you think we need in your answers so 
[normal]that 
[normal]we are educated?  
[normal]Could each of you 
[normal]just 
[normal]describe 
[normal]to us what you think the term “open data”
[normal] 
[normal]actually 
[normal]means?  
[normal]Professor Margetts:[bold] 
[normal]“
[normal]Open data
[normal]”
[normal] is an interesting term and it gets many terms bundled into it.  In some ways, open data is a bit like the little white bunny of 
[normal]g
[normal]overnment.  It means something nice, warm and good that will aid democracy.  It is a confused term
[normal],
[normal] though
[normal],
[normal] because it implies that it is just opening data up for public use.  In the loosest sense
[normal],
[normal] that would be a term
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]but 
[normal]some people use 
[normal]it 
[normal]to mean open government; some people use it to mean big data
[normal]—
[normal]data that can be used for a particular kind of analysis.  
[normal]The confusion comes from the fact that it basically has three aims
[normal],
[normal] and you will see all these aims mentioned by different people
[normal]—
[normal]and even the same people.  
[normal]They are: greater transparency; 
[normal]improving 
[normal]g
[normal]overnment
[normal], as 
[normal]somehow open 
[normal]data 
[normal]will make 
[normal]g
[normal]overnment better
[normal]; 
[normal]and 
[normal]encourag
[normal]ing
[normal] innovation and enterprise in the wider commercial world.  That is where the confusion comes from.  
[normal]Dr Worthy:[bold] You have Rufus Pollock from the Open Knowledge Foundation 
[normal]speaking 
[normal]later.  
[normal]It has 
[normal]a very good definition of open data: information that is reusable
[normal] and accessible to all, 
[normal]and can be read by a machine.  That is a very simple definition.  Helen is exactly right in what she says.  T
[normal]he problem is that it is conflated with lots of other ideas
[normal] and there 
[normal]is an assumption that open data means open government, for example.  
[normal]There are quite a lot of assumptions built into an idea like 
[normal]that—
[normal]that open data then automatically leads to transparency and accountability of 
[normal]g
[normal]overnment.  
[normal]Q3 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair[bold]:[bold] What is the difference between open data and open government?  
[normal]Dr Worthy:[bold] 
[normal]Open 
[normal]data is about technology and
[normal] making something machine
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]readable.  Open 
[normal]government brings in more political ideas about making government accountable and answerable.  
[normal]For example, 
[normal]f
[normal]reedom of 
[normal]i
[normal]nformation is about accessing information.  Open data is about re-using information and doing interesting and new things with it to gain new understandings.  
[normal]There is considerable overlap there, but they are not necessarily the same thing
[normal], not least because the Government can control what open data is given out.  
[normal]Q4 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair[bold]:[bold] How well does each of you think the Government understands this?  
[normal]Professor Margetts:[bold] Not very well.  
[normal]Q5 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair[bold]:[bold] 
[normal]Thank you.  
[normal]Why was that so hard to say?  
[normal]Professor Margetts:[bold] 
[normal]For the reason I 
[normal]gave
[normal].  To criticise open data is a bit like saying you do not like babies: you are not supposed to say it.  It is true that it has very noble aims
[normal],
[normal] and most of the people who are great advocates of open data have the three noble aims that I mentioned.  The point is that there is an idea that open data will somehow automatically lead to open government
[normal],
[normal] and that is by no means the case.  
[normal]Q6 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair[bold]:[bold] 
[normal]Dr Worthy, d
[normal]o you think in 
[normal]g
[normal]overnment there is a sense that they just need to be in favour of it and it 
[normal]all 
[normal]will happen, whatever 
[normal]“
[normal]it
[normal]”
[normal] is?  
[normal]Dr Worthy:[bold] 
[normal]It is a bit like the idea of transparency.  Transparency is just a good thing in all situations
[normal],
[normal] and it is so deeply embedded as a good thing that it is difficult to argue about the nuances.  
[normal]What Helen says is exactly right.  There are so many aims attached to open data.  
[normal]There are economic aims about hunting down waste and encouraging use by business.  
[normal]There are political aims about participation and transparency.  
[normal]There are social aims about empowering communities.  There are so many
[normal],
[normal] and one of the things I have been finding in my interviews is that local government, from its perspective, 
[normal]finds that central Government 
[normal]are 
[normal]switching between different aims and 
[normal]shifting 
[normal]the 
[normal]emphasis.  
[normal]They are not exactly sure what it is they are supposed to see, whom they are supposed to be targeting with this data and what effects should be coming out of it.  
[normal]Q7 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Kelvin [bold]Hopkins[bold]:[bold] 
[normal]You implied that open data means open government, but open data has to have a licence
[normal],
[normal] as I understand
[normal] it,
[normal] and there is also closed data.  
[normal]The Government can choose if things are open or closed.  
[normal]Is that right?  
[normal]Dr Worthy:[bold] Yes.  
[normal]Professor Margetts:[bold] Yes, Government Departments have to release data, but they can 
[normal]to a large extent 
[normal]choose 
[normal]which data to release and which data not to release.  T
[normal]hey cannot release 
[normal]some data 
[normal]because it is personal data
[normal] or 
[normal]if 
[normal]there would be strong ethical or legal barriers to them doing so.  
[normal]Dr Worthy:[bold] 
[normal]That is one of the fundamental differences to bear in mind between open data and open government.  If you compare open data with f
[normal]reedom of information, open data is 
[normal]still 
[normal]what 
[normal]the 
[normal]G
[normal]overnment choose
[normal] to release
[normal] or emphasise.  With freedom of information
[normal],
[normal] you can ask for many different things, some of which 
[normal]the Government probably do
[normal] not necessarily want you to ask for.  
[normal]There is more of a sense that the Government cannot control 
[normal]exactly 
[normal]what has been asked for
[normal] with FOI
[normal].  
[normal]There is a distinction.  
[normal]Q8 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair[bold]:[bold] 
[normal]If a graduate brought to you the 
[normal]o
[normal]pen 
[normal]d
