[normal]Some leaders may see this as something that they should just minimally comply with.  There 
[normal]is also an issue of resources.  Some local authorities are locked into particular contracts with technology and software, so they can only do certain things.  
[normal]It may 
[normal]also 
[normal]be an issue about skills
[normal]: t
[normal]o rea
[normal]lly take advantage of this data, link it
[normal] to other pieces of information; 
[normal]and to help with innovations
[normal],
[normal] you 
[normal]need particular skills
[normal] that not all authorities or public bodies may have ready access to.  One solution is to make sure that public bodies do work closely with innovators who do have this level of skills.  
[normal]Q25 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Reed:[bold] Do you recognise there would perhaps be a risk 
[normal]that 
[normal]some politicians would feel that
[normal],
[normal] if you moved towards
[normal] publishing data around street-level spend, as you mentioned earlier, that could create an impetus towards equalising spend per capita
[normal],
[normal] rather than focusing spend on areas or households with greater levels of deprivation or social exclusion
[normal],
[normal] who would be 
[normal]generally less articulate
[normal]?
[normal]Dr Worthy:[bold] 
[normal]Looking at local government especially, I have found that 
[normal]although technology is 
[normal]often 
[normal]presented as a neutral good
[normal],
[normal] it is extremely political.  
[normal]The local government spending data is very politicised.  It is about local versus central 
[normal]G
[normal]overnment.  Some interviewees have spoken of how they feel that the spending data is presented in a particular way to make it look like local authorities are profligate wasters of money.  
[normal]Regarding t
[normal]he way in which you see it now
[normal],
[normal] with the £500 spends
[normal],
[normal] there are automatically words like “bar bills” and you see how much money
[normal] was spent
[normal].  
[normal]The 
[normal]way you present the data can frame what you think.  
[normal]There is much less information in their spend data about what impact the money has and much more about the fact that it has been spent, which biases you to understand spending in a particular way.  
[normal]Whatever way you push it
[normal],
[normal] there are risks that it can have all sorts of effects
[normal], not least because how people behave when 
[normal]given 
[normal]information is very nuanced and subjective.  It is 
[normal]not simply that they get 
[normal]a 
[normal]piece of information and then do 
[normal]X
