[normal]              [bold]Chair[bold]:[bold] Right, that is one recommendation.  
[normal]Tom Steinberg[bold]: 
[normal]There are t
[normal]wo things from me 
[normal]that 
[normal]both relate to the fact that the discussion in the last few years has been much too much about whether we can get this 
[normal]or that data set out.  The laws that this Parliament passes do not ever tend to be about really specific things; they are not about one person or one company.  They tend to be about classes of companies and classes of people.  
[normal]We need two kinds of new law that do not exist at the moment.  One is about 
[normal]g
[normal]overnment procurement of computer systems
[normal] that simply says all parts of 
[normal]g
[normal]overnment, whether large or small, must not or cannot procure anything digital or electronic of any kind that does not make the production of open data essentially available at zero marginal cost beyond the contract value
[normal].  
[normal]The reason that should be there is 
[normal]because 
[normal]it does not cost anything else.  
[normal]It is a bit like if you are building a brand new house and you want to make it easy for someone disabled to live in
[normal]: 
[normal]it 
[normal]is incredibly cheap 
[normal]to build it in at first compared 
[normal]with 
[normal]taking
[normal] a building like this and try
