[normal]Dr Pollock:[bold] 
[normal]T
[normal]o add 
[normal]just 
[normal]one thing to that, 
[normal]the definition of 
[normal]o
[normal]pen data at opendefinition.org does include machine-readability as a
[normal] principle.  
[normal]You always have those stories in movies where the plucky defence are trying to sue this big company and they get given 500 box files of paper to read through.  There is a way to prevent the use of open data
[normal]:
[normal] by giving people material in a way they cannot process very easily.  Paper is not machine-readable.  A computer cannot read your handwriting very well yet, and all these kinds of things.  That is a requirement.  
[normal]The key thing to say is that once you have given out 
[normal]something 
[normal]machine
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]readable
[normal]—
[normal]and by that I mean a spreadsheet versus a document with a table written on it
[normal]—
[normal]do not get too worried about the format.  While geeks will complain
[normal] and they will say, “You gave me Excel when you should have given me something else
[normal],
[normal]” or whatever, in 
[normal]general once it is in that structure
[normal],
[normal] people who are motivated enough will be able to use it
[normal] or convert it
[normal].  
[normal]The one addendum to that is when you are missing some essential piece of information.  A classic example
[normal], which
[normal] is where it gets more subtle at the moment
[normal], is that 
[normal]the 
[normal]Government give out very 
[normal]detailed 
[normal]spending information
[normal] now
