[normal]They now give
[normal] out contract information.  You might think you would like to put those two bits of data together more effectively.  Unfortunately, in the spending information
[normal],
[normal] you do not tend to get the contract number that that spending relates to
[normal],
[normal] if there is a contract.  
[normal]That is where we get a little bit subtle, but often missing that key piece of information 
[normal]makes it very difficult to join up data sets
[normal] that would give you insight through that joining up. Heather talks about connective tissue
[normal]—
[normal]addresses or postcodes
[normal]: 
[normal]every citizen in the 
[normal]UK
[normal] knows their postcode.  
[normal]However, i
[normal]f I said to you, “Do you know your longitude and latitude?” you will not.  
[normal]Those are 
[normal]often 
[normal]key moments
[normal] where people, for example, know their geographic information.  T
[normal]here are so many services you
[normal] could use, such as when you go to Amazon or when you go to pay your gas bill.  There are so many things that use your postcode; it is a connection between so many datasets
[normal],
[normal] because it 
[normal]gives
[normal] your geographic information, which then allows you to connect into other data sets.  That is a key point that is difficult in general to legislate.  The key point is that we want to be able to connect data together.  That is a key point
[normal]:
[normal] the power of open data is that it enables us to connect things together and therefore 
[normal]to 
[normal]gain better insight by joining up sets of information.  
