[normal]Heather Savory[bold]: There are several questions here.  As Tom rightly said, there are ubiquitous digital standards for data ranging from CSV to Excel data
[normal]—
[normal]as in normal Excel spreadsheets
[normal]—
[normal]and up to linked data.  You may know that there is considerable work being done at the Web 3.0 Consortium about linked data.  The premise is that the tech community can cope.  You do not want to be re-inventing or prescribing specific things.  There are preferred standards; the preference is to deliver things in
[normal] a
[normal] machine-readable format that technical people can cope with.  I would also like to say that there are now lots of cheap or free platforms on which you can do data analysis
[normal] 
[normal]using free software
[normal].  It is not just the highly technical people who can deal with these data sets.  One of the things we push for 
[normal]is 
[normal]more APIs.  An API is something that allows you to pull out your own set of data from a big set of data.  You can say, “I want this, this, this and this
[normal],
[normal]” and you can extract it out.  Whilst these standards all exist and there is a plethora of different things being delivered, the primary thing is that a document or a PDF is not a piece of
[normal] open
[normal] data.  We have now got that far
[normal]—
[normal]that is not open data.  
[normal]Across Government and all public sector bodies
[normal],
[normal] we need some more help
[normal]—
[normal]not to say, “You must 
[normal]do
[normal] X, Y and Z,” 
[normal]but
[normal] giving us another way that you can get data out.  One of the things that happens at the moment because of the silo nature of Departments and public bodies is that I expect there is some committee somewhere and then some poor chap sitting down in the basement
[normal]—
[normal]because IT people never have windows
[normal]—
[normal]and somebody will come knocking on the door and say, “You’ve got to deliver that as open data
[normal].
[normal]”  This poor guy will be going, “I wonder what that means.  What do I do?”  Then whoever it is will go back upstairs and carry on with their policy job
[normal],
[normal] because we have told him this organisation is going to be delivering open data.  
[normal]Some technical guidance would be useful across 
[normal]Whitehall
[normal] to give people more assistance about the preferred ways and challenges of delivering this open data.  Some people will find it easier than others.  I fully support the changes to the procurement rules because, as Tom has said, building in the method of delivering this data does put it at a real margin
[normal]al
[normal] cost.  You might be astonished that
[normal],
[normal] with current systems
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]our
[normal] data 
[normal]is sometimes 
[normal]locked up 
[normal]and
[normal] 
[normal]some of the incumbent IT suppliers to Government charge us for getting
[normal] that
[normal] data
[normal],
[normal] because they have to extract it and nobody else can do that.  That is fundamental to moving the agenda forward and making it work.  
[normal]The other thing that I would just point the Committee to is that the Open Data Institute has just released a certificate
[normal]—
[normal]a method where you can go and self-rate your own open data.  It is in beta; you can find it on 
[normal]its 
[normal]website.  That is a really useful tool for the community because it has all the bits that you need to know.  I would say it is a little bit fluffy in terms of supply and release dates
[normal],
[normal] because if I am going to build a business based on this data
[normal],
[normal] I want to know that it is going to be maintained.  It is no good having a data set now, updating it in six months and then leaving it for three years
[normal],
[normal] because my business will be dependent on it.  This shows you w
[normal]h
[normal]ere you can get it and it gives a good indicator of the quality of the data, so I think it would be a very positive move to have that and some sort of help or guidance note that went across the picture.  
[normal]There is one technical point I wanted to bring up in legislation terms.  I have to refer to my notes here; I have to get it right.  There is the Freedom of Information Act and there was a Protection of Freedoms Act 2012.  This is regulation that has just been brought into force
[normal],
[normal] and this established an enhanced right to data because it introduces a statutory duty for public authorities to publish their data for re-use.  I absolutely agree we do not have clean legislation.  There is not an Open Data Act, but if you look at the complex network of legislation that we have
[normal],
[normal] there is already a presumption to publish data and there are duties for public bodies to make their data available for re-use.  
