[normal] what happens in the bad times
[normal]?  
[normal]In the bad times
[normal],
[normal] everyone gets their hair cut
[normal],
[normal] and suddenly you cannot do your mapping anymore.  One way to run that is to have an independent regulator who both guarantees that they are at arm
[normal]’
[normal]s length
[normal]—they
[normal] get provided money by the Government
[normal]—
[normal]but at the same time monitors quality and other things.  There is a question at the moment of what happens if people complain?  At the moment
[normal],
[normal] they can come to the Open Data User Group and we can go to the Cabinet Office and complain, but it is not a very enforceable structure regarding access to some of these things.  You have the Information Commissioner and things around other stuff, and one of the recommendations is having some proper regulatory oversight of this going forward that we do not really have today.  
[normal]Tom Steinberg[bold]: This was the issue over which I decided that I would no longer be on the Transparency Board.  
[normal]A
[normal] group of six civil servants from different Departments got on the telephone to tell me that the idea of independent regulation was not worthy for what are essentially entities
[normal]—
[normal]trading funds that
[normal],
[normal] if they want
[normal],
[normal] can just shave margin off every business and bit of 
[normal]government 
[normal]in the country with no challenge.  They told me it was a stupid and bureaucratic idea.  
[normal]Q67 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Six civil servants sounds like a campaign.  
[normal]Tom Steinberg[bold]: You asked me before which Department was most problematic
[normal],
[normal] and I gave a non-answer
[normal],
