[normal]something very significant personally about someone.  There is clearly going to be ongoing debate.  
[normal]I do not think there is an easy answer to this
[normal],
[normal] and I think it is going to be one where some of the most interesting data 
[normal]will have
[normal] a relationship with personal information
[normal]—
[normal]crime statistics or crime data, in fact.  
[normal]T
[normal]he default position has to be that we protect privacy in the first instance, but it is important that there are cases where we make public interest trade-offs.  We think that we are entitled to know the directors of public companies; it is not something that is private.  By having a limited liability company
[normal],
[normal] you give up your right to 
[normal]privacy—people
[normal] know that you are a director.  Those are going to be interesting questions.  The really interesting question over the next 10, 20 or 30 years is how we make the trade-offs between privacy and public interest in a variety of areas.  One has been around the VAT register
[normal]—
[normal]should the VAT register not be published because it possibly has privacy implications?  
[normal]              
[normal]Q72 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Kelvin [bold]Hopkins[bold]:[bold] There are some countries, such as in 
[normal]Scandinavia
[normal], w
[normal]h
[normal]ere they publish people’s personal tax returns and so on.  That sort of privacy is thought to be unacceptable in a democracy
[normal]—
[normal]that we
[normal] ought to know
[normal].
[normal]  We tend to be much more worried about privacy.  
[normal]              [bold]Chair:[bold] Can we let the other witnesses answer your original question?  
[normal]Heather Savory[bold]: I agree with you that it is a cultural issue.  I am quite interested to see what happens in the next generation
[normal],
[normal] because they just work in such a different way.  They communicate differently
[normal].  They 
[normal]have a lot of private information available
[normal] and 
[normal]seem to be far less fazed by it all, 
[normal]although 
[normal]that could turn around.  
[normal]The VAT register is quite interesting because it is a good case study of what happens with Departments.  We have this with the VAT register and we have it with DVLA data as well.  The thing is, “We can’t open up the data because we’ll increase fraud
[normal],
[normal] and personal data will be there
[normal].
[normal]”  This is coming back to the attitudes about it.  With the VAT register
[normal],
[normal] we found there is actually an EU site you can go to, VIES, where you can go and type any member state, VAT number
[normal],
[normal] and it gives you the address.  Sometimes you find that these issues of privacy have already been superseded.  People do not actually know how much information is available about them.  It is only when you start talking about releasing it as bulk data that people start to get concerned about it.  
[normal]Having said that, we want open data but we do not want to compromise privacy.  As Rufus has said, we have to make some decisions about how to anonymise data.  There are some really quite serious working groups at the moment looking at anonymisation and pseudonimisation of data so that you can release these data sets in a way that 
[normal]means 
[normal]they can be hugely beneficial, but without identifying individuals.  
[normal]My last point is cultural.  When you ask citizens to put their personal data up for a good cause like the Human Genome Project or various health projects
[normal],
[normal] you find a totally different attitude.  If people feel they are giving their data in a beneficial way
[normal],
[normal] they are much more open to allowing it to be used for research, etc.  
[normal]Q73 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Can I just probe on one particular question, which is this generational difference?  How do you think that can be reflected in Government policy
[normal],
[normal] or does Government policy have to evolve with changing generational attitudes towards privacy?  
[normal]Tom Steinberg[bold]: Yes.  Step one is accepting the fact that values in this field are changing really fast and changing in ways we do not fully understand yet.  
[normal]That means understanding 
[normal]that
[normal],
[normal] unlike legislation for a crime, where you are pretty sure people will think that is wrong today and still think it wrong in 20 years’ time
[normal], instead 
[normal]you have to think of this much more like something that is inevitably going to change quite quickly.  I would argue that if Parliament has a role here
[normal],
[normal] it is probably to make sure that there is some kind of regular review that is much faster than normal, decade-long legislative cycles 
[normal]and 
[normal]can cope with the fact that what is acceptable today may even have changed in acceptability in just two or three years’ time.  I would like to see Parliament say every 12 months or every 24 months the Government 
[normal]are 
[normal]essentially going to be tasked 
[normal]to assess 
[normal]what is normal, or Parliament itself will meet to discuss what is now acceptable and what is not acceptable in this trade-off between privacy and public.  The only thing that is permanent is the decision to review it very regularly in a way that there rest of the public sector can understand.  
[normal]The public sector really needs some guidance that lands on their desks that basically goes, “These kinds of trade-offs are okay and these kinds are not
[normal],
[normal]” because you are never goi
[normal]ng to be able to draw a crystal-
[normal]clear legal definitional line between them.  It is not going to exist in this field; it is all shades of grey.  What you can give people
[normal],
[normal] though
[normal],
[normal] is five examples 
[normal]of what 
[normal]Members here vote in a majority to say are acceptable trade-offs and five that are not.  Review those in two years and there might be a different five and a different five.  I would love to see a decade in which we prepared for the knowledge that these values are going to change so quickly and that the political and technical context is going to change very quickly, and that in the diary we know when it is going to be next revised
[normal],
[normal] even though it has not happened yet.  That would be a great step forward.  
[normal]Q74 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Reed:[bold] I will just confine myself to one question.  
[normal]Chair:[bold] 
[normal]That is
[normal] economic
[normal] innovation and 
[normal]so on
[normal].  Mr Pollock, can you take the first answer because I know you have to leave?
[normal]Mr Reed:[bold] How well do
[normal] the Government understand the needs of different commercial users of open data?  
[normal]Dr Pollock:[bold] It is a difficult question because there are so many.  Heather has emphasised that sometimes it is quite 
[normal]well known
[normal] what 
[normal]some of 
[normal]those desires are, but the challenge is often they are the ones the Government 
[normal]are 
[normal]least inclined to satisfy for other reaso
[normal]ns.  I think the Government do
[normal] have a sense
[normal] of that
[normal], but a key point is that much of this is about innovation.  It is always a challenge of doing stuff: maybe it is people who are 10 or 15 today who are going to build a company in two, three or five years.  It is very difficult because they are not normally the people who come to this room or even know yet what their wants are.  
[normal]One of our lessons of innovation, particularly in the digital space, is that you do not know what you are going to build
[normal],
[normal] and often when you think you know what you are going to build
[normal],
[normal] you are wrong.  In that sense, the whole point of opening up data is that it is the unexpected.  It is the many-minds principle.  The best thing to do with your data will be thought of by someone else, not by you.  That aspect is essential to this.  In a way, it is currently a debate about high
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]value/low
[normal]&#x2011;
[normal]value data sets.  There are some things we can see now there are desires for, but some of the things that are most interesting we are not going to anticipate.  Maybe someone will come up with a credible way to spot tax evasion or tax avoidance, or better ways to look at benefit fraud, or better ways to identify how 
[normal]g
[normal]overnment saves money.  Those are the most unexpected aspects of this
[normal],
[normal] and we are not sure where th
[normal]e
[normal]y will come from.  It may be some other data set that we cannot even think of.  
[normal]That is one of the 
[normal]fundamental 
[normal]points here, in the sense that it is very difficult for commercial entities.  Google could come and tell us, but those that are most exciting and most interesting I think would find it very difficult to come and tell us.  This is why “
[normal]get 
[normal]it out there” is the general approach.  
[normal]Q75 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Mr Reed:[bold] Is there any way that 
[normal]g
[normal]overnment can engage with that kind of dynamic, entrepreneurial fast-moving world?  
[normal]Dr Pollock:[bold] Go to events.  Get out of 
[normal]g
[normal]overnment and do not run consultations.  That is my other big point.  People who write responses to consultations, even me
[normal],
[normal] are busy
[normal]—
[normal]technical innovators are busy.  Go to where they are.  Go to their meet-ups, go to their events, go to their conferences and listen to them.  Unfortunately
[normal], 
[normal]sometimes the Government in other times 
[normal]have 
[normal]said
[normal], “No one has a travel budget to get anywhere.
[normal]”
[normal]  Go to those things; it sometimes means people
[normal] have to do it
[normal] in their spare time.  They happen in evenings or weekends, or require you to travel to another country.  Go to where they are and listen to them.  
[normal]Heather Savory[bold]: 
[normal]That is actually one of the reasons I am here
[normal],
[normal] because obviously the Open Data User Group was set up to try 
[normal]to
[normal] improve that.  
[normal]In terms of Government understanding, I think one o
[normal]f the things the Government do
[normal] not understand is how big companies need this data.  I have something to wave at you as an example.  This is done by Deloitte
[normal],
[normal] and it is using open data.  It is a demographic analysis of how population is moving and where current bank branch networks are.  Nobody likes the banks much at one level, but they are very important in our society.  This shows that retired people are all moving to the seaside
[normal],
[normal] and it shows that young, upwardly mobile people are moving into cities.  This is based on open data.  This is why companies that you do not think of as needing open data need this open data.  These are the utilities companies, Sainsbury’s, Tesco, etc.  
[normal]              
[normal]On the start-up side
[normal],
[normal] we need to make more of case studies.  One of the things I want to do this year is to try 
[normal]to 
[normal]promote some of the really good examples of businesses built on open data.  We need to gain confidence, particularly within the Treasury, 
[normal]so 
[normal]that this 
[normal]out-of-
[normal]balance 
[normal]“
[normal]small amount of money for big benefit
[normal]”
[normal] could be tipped when 
[normal]they 
[normal]start to see some tangible results.  
[normal]The primary 
[normal]thing
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]which 
[normal]comes back to what both my colleagues here have said
[normal],
[normal] is about pace.  Government just does not understand the difference in pace between 
[normal]Whitehall
[normal] and Departments, and then somewhere along the line there are other public sector bodies
[normal],
[normal] and the business world, and businesses of all size.  For example, we have had 500 data requests since last year.  They are all moving slowly through the system and some of them are now coming to fruition.  What these start-up companies want is if it is a “no” because of private data issues
[normal],
[normal] it needs to be “no” tomorrow
[normal],
[normal] because then they will go and do something different.  Then in 
[normal]Whitehall
[normal] everyone is saying, “You’re not doing badly, are you?  Things are moving really quickly, aren’t they?” and then I have my group saying, “This is glacial
[normal].”
[normal]  
[normal]There are
[normal] two cultures 
[normal]there.
[normal]Q76 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] Do you think this is all tainted by a Sir
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Humphrey disdain for the idea that people should make money out of public data
[normal]—
[normal]that there is something rather distasteful about it?  
[normal]Heather Savory[bold]: There are definitely some individuals I have met during the course of the last year who do not seem to understand the fundamental connection between making money, paying tax and delivering public services.  I found that quite shocking.  This is a virtuous circle.  
[normal]Tom Steinberg[bold]: Can I just answer your question? 
[normal] 
[normal]I slightly take issue with the idea that the Government should nee
[normal]d
[normal] to understand much about me.  If I have truly amazing, wonderful new idea, it is entirely likely that no
[normal] 
[normal]one understands it except me, let alone the people on the other side of the table.  Luckily they got rid of this, but it used to be that the Ordnance Survey asked for your business model so that 
[normal]it 
[normal]could read it and understand your need.  At one level
[normal],
[normal] that sounds like it makes sense, but at another level the mom
[normal]ent you say the Government need
[normal] to understand what someone needs some data for
[normal] 
[normal]is the moment you say
[normal],
[normal] 
[normal]“O
[normal]ur Government’s data policy has basically excluded true innovation.
[normal]”
[normal]  
[normal]The nature of innovation is often to see value where other people just cannot see it.  No
[normal] 
[normal]one saw that there was much value in a list of Harvard undergraduates except Mark
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Zuckerberg; no one saw there was much value in the links on the internet pointing to other websites except the people who founded Google.  A characteristic of some digital innovation is precisely people seeing value.  If the Government 
[normal]are 
[normal]set up to say, “We’ll give it to you if we understand the value
[normal],
[normal]” that is just basically a way of saying, “We wouldn’t like any innovative companies, please
[normal].
[normal]”  I would like it to be thought of in a rights model much more than in an unders
[normal]tanding model.  That is to say: 
[normal]if I tell you that it is important to me and it does not place an unreasonable burden on the public sector
[normal],
[normal] I will get it.  Merely by coincidence, that is how the Freedom of Information Act is structured at the moment.  It does not work
[normal],
[normal] though
[normal],
[normal] if I go and ask the Government for some bit of data.  That is very much how it needs to work, precisely with the 
[normal]18-year-
[normal]old Rufus talked about
[normal],
[normal] who is not going to know how to make a value case to a civil servant in civil servant language.  
[normal]Dr Pollock:[bold] You need to connect to the electricity grid
[normal]: “
[normal]Can you tell us why you need electricity to run your factory?”
[normal]Q77 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] You would be surprised.
[normal]Can I ask one final question?  Stephan Shakespeare talks about how our country could be at the front of a wave of innovation that would provide another big service industry we would export all over the world as other countries move to open data.  Do you agree with that analysis or that conjecture?  
[normal]Could 
[normal]we 
[normal]be 
[normal]the home of all the new apps, applications and development
[normal]?
[normal]  
[normal]Dr Pollock:[bold] It is definitely possible.  There are big forces at work, but one example often given of where we failed was that the 
[normal]US
[normal] opened up geographic information in the 
[normal]’
[normal]80s.  It was v
[normal]ery liberal about access to geo-
[normal]information and we were not; we actually shut it down under Thatcher by charging more 
[normal]and Ordnance
[normal] 
[normal]S
[normal]urvey
[normal] 
[normal]moving to the trading fund model quite aggressively.  It is always cited
[normal];
[normal] there is the famous 
[normal]saying 
[normal]by 
[normal]Weiss
[normal] 
[normal]where he is saying in the 
[normal]US
[normal] you have this really big geographic information system industry.  There are people selling geographic software, not selling data.  There is also the example of weather derivatives as well in the US, where access to free weather data made it much easier to build a weather derivatives market
[normal],
[normal] where you could insure weather risk much better and more efficiently.  There is that possibility.  The world moves fast
[normal],
[normal] so we need to do that.  There is potential.  There is going to be competition in that space
[normal],
[normal] and it relates to the software industry and other things.  It relates to having a good venture capital industry and having a good set of people who are trained in data and information skills.  We run the 
[normal]School
[normal] of 
[normal]Data
[normal] because we think all this data coming out is great, but do people know how to use it, particularly people who are not data geeks?  That is the other challenge.  It is not just going to be the data out there; it is going to be the skills, the infrastructure and the funding to build the businesses to do that as well.
[normal]Chair:[bold] I think that was a yes.  
[normal]Dr Pollock:[bold] Yes, that was a yes.  
[normal]Heather Savory[bold]: I got slightly confuse
[normal]d
[normal] by your question because I think there are two aspects to this.  There is the 
[normal]UK
[normal]’s skill at open data
[normal], 
[normal]which is what I suddenly thought you might be asking.  To what extent can we influence other countries and share our best
[normal] 
[normal]practice in terms of what we do here?  I think the answer there is yes
[normal],
[normal] because we are at the front of the field.  I agree with what Rufus is saying there.  There is absolutely a skill shortage.  
[normal]A
[normal] lot of techy friends are now delighted because somebody has said that being a data scientist is going to be the sexiest job in the 21
[normal]st
[normal] century.  That is actually true: there are opportunities.  We need those skills.  We also need to make sure that the financiers really can depend on this source of material.  That is fundamental.  I am not going to back a business if I do not think that this data is going to be available in two years’ time. 
[normal]Q78 [bold]&#xa0; 
[normal]Chair:[bold] The rights-based model rather than a permission-based model.  I understand that.  
[normal]Tom Steinberg[bold]: I think we have almost everything we need to be building the 2013 versions of the 1990s and 
[normal]’
[normal]80s tools that were mentioned there.  You mentioned earlier on the idea of a tool that could tell you how much public money had been spent in an area.  Someone can get paid to build that tool and someone can get paid for selling it to Governments around the world.  It will get built in the country where the data to power 
[normal]it 
[normal]is available
